  "passageParts": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "Most of us strive for self-respect — to see ourselves in a positive light, to be\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 1
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nof who we are. Any comments or experiences that undermine those feelings of self-worth can be uncomfortable and it's only\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 2
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto want to avoid them. But the thing is,\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 3
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nyour self-worth really is being undermined is, to a large degree, subjective. Much of it comes down to your\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 4
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nof what someone said or did.\n When you take things personally, you're interpreting these situations as saying something significant and negative about you as a person. Say your boss picks holes in your sales report, and you come away feeling like this means she thinks you're a\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 5
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nmember of staff. Or, two of your friends cancel your\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 6
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nget-together at the pub and you interpret this as meaning they're bored of you. Psychologists have a\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 7
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nfor this way of thinking: personalisation. But the\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 8
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nis that your boss might view you very highly. It's just you made some\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 9
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nin the report and she wanted to point these out so that you do better next time.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 10
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​, in the case of your friends cancelling, perhaps they both felt unwell that weekend or they just\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 11
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\ntheir minds.\n In both\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 12
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\n— and others that we all experience — there’s another\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 13
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nat work that psychologists call mind reading. This is when you assume to know what other people are thinking about you, when you can’t really know without\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 14
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthem directly.\n One simple way to avoid\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 15
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\npersonalisation and mind reading is to challenge your negative assumptions of what’s\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 16
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​. When you find yourself taking a situation personally, try to think of other interpretations that are less focused on you — especially in the sense of saying anything deep or\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 17
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nabout you.\n When you do this, it might help to try to put yourself in other people’s shoes. The fact your boss took the time to give you\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 18
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nat all means they care enough to want to help you\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​. When it comes to your friends — maybe it’s because your friendship is so\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthat they felt able to cancel at late notice."
    }
  ],
